{#def is_mac, is_authenticated, mngr_forward_origin, initial_workspaces, agent_iframe_src="about:blank", initial_accent="" #}
{#
  Agent-content wrapper page (titlebar + sidebar + content iframe).

  The titlebar + browser-mode sidebar + accent / chrome.js wiring live in the
  shared ChromeShell layout; this page fills ChromeShell's content slot with the
  browser-mode content surface (the #content-frame iframe, backed by the white
  mirror). In Electron mode the iframe and embedded browser-mode sidebar are
  hidden via JS; the content is a separate WebContentsView, and the sidebar page
  is loaded into the shared modal WebContentsView when opened.

  ``initial_accent`` (a #rrggbb, when this wrapper is loaded for a specific
  workspace) seeds ``--titlebar-bg`` inline in the head so the FIRST paint of a
  freshly (re)loaded wrapper already carries the workspace accent. Without it the
  new renderer paints a neutral titlebar until chrome.js is primed on
  did-finish-load -- so navigating landing->workspace or settings->workspace
  flashed the titlebar white->accent->white->accent instead of a single
  white->accent. chrome.js's later ``documentElement.style`` set (same value)
  overrides this inline rule seamlessly.

  ``agent_iframe_src`` is the workspace (agent) URL the iframe shows in BROWSER
  mode -- the server passes the ``/goto/<agent>/`` URL when this wrapper is
  requested for a specific workspace (``/_chrome?workspace=<agent-id>``), else
  ``about:blank``. It is NEVER a trusted local page like ``/`` (which would render
  its own ChromeShell titlebar inside the iframe -- a doubled titlebar). In
  Electron the iframe is hidden (the real content is a separate WebContentsView),
  so the value is inert there.

  is_mac controls macOS-specific styling (traffic-light padding, hidden window
  controls). mngr_forward_origin is exposed to page-level JS via a data attribute
  on the body so chrome.js can build workspace links that target the plugin's
  port directly.
#}
{# Body background tracks --titlebar-bg (ChromeShell's default) so the iframe's
   rounded top corners (browser mode) and the chromeView's extension strip
   (Electron mode) both reveal accent color through the curve. Falls back to the
   neutral app surface (surface-primary -- white in light, black in dark) when no
   workspace is active. #}
{# Seed the accent inline (before chrome.js runs) so the first paint isn't
   neutral. Forwarded through ChromeShell's ``head`` slot. #}
{% set _accent_head %}{% if initial_accent %}<style>:root {
        --titlebar-bg: {{ initial_accent }};
      }</style>{% endif %}{% endset %}
<ChromeShell title="Minds"
             :is_mac="is_mac"
             :is_authenticated="is_authenticated"
             :mngr_forward_origin="mngr_forward_origin"
             :is_agent_content_surface="True"
             head={{ _accent_head }}>
  {# White "mirror" sized exactly like the Electron contentView (left:4
     / top:38 / right:4 / bottom:4 / radius:12 -- matches CONTENT_INSET
     and CONTENT_CORNER_RADIUS in electron/main.js). Sits behind the
     iframe in browser mode (the iframe covers it completely so it's
     invisible there) and shows through in Electron mode whenever the
     WebContentsView's compositor surface goes briefly transparent --
     which Chromium does on cross-origin history navigation
     (goBack/goForward between Home and a workspace), between the old
     frame tearing down and the new frame's first paint. Without this
     mirror the chromeView body's accent color would flash through.
     Pointer-events:none so it never intercepts clicks. #}
  <div id="content-bg-mirror"
       class="fixed left-[4px] top-[38px] rounded-[12px] bg-surface-primary pointer-events-none"
       style="width: calc(100% - 8px); height: calc(100% - 42px);"></div>

  <iframe id="content-frame"
          src="{{ agent_iframe_src }}"
          class="fixed left-[4px] top-[38px] border-0 rounded-[12px] bg-surface-primary"
          style="width: calc(100% - 8px); height: calc(100% - 42px); box-shadow: 0 1px 0 rgba(255,255,255,0.05) inset;"></iframe>
</ChromeShell>
